05992nam a22008295i 9780231547598DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019016862  a97802315475987 a10.7312/jeps187962doi  a(DE-B1597)544649  a(OCoLC)1134852959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHC59.7b.J48 2019 4aHC59.7b.J48 2020 7aBUS0690202bisacsh04a338.9009172/42231 aJepson, Nicholas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn China's Wake :bHow the Commodity Boom Transformed Development Strategies in the Global South /cNicholas Jepson. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b19 b&w charts and graphs, 21 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tI. World Markets in China’s Wake -- tII. Natural Resources and Development Under Shifting Global Regimes -- tIII. The Rise of China as a Necessary Condition for Post- Neoliberal Breaks -- tIV. A Typology of Political- Economic Trajectories Under Commodity Boom Conditions -- tV. Neodevelopmentalist Type: Argentina and Brazil -- tVI. Extractivist- Redistributive Type: Ecuador, Bolivia, and Venezuela -- tVII. Extractivist- Oligarchic Type: Angola and Kazakhstan -- tVIII. Donor- Dependent Orthodoxy Type: Zambia, Laos, and Mongolia -- tIX. Homegrown Orthodoxy Type: Jamaica, Peru, South Africa, Colombia, and Indonesia -- tX. China and Global Transformation -- tAppendix: Research Design— Qualitative Comparative Analysis and Interviews -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 2000s, Chinese demand for imported commodities ballooned as the country continued its breakneck economic growth. Simultaneously, global markets in metals and fuels experienced a boom of unprecedented extent and duration. Meanwhile, resource-rich states in the Global South from Argentina to Angola began to advance a range of new development strategies, breaking away from the economic orthodoxies to which they had long appeared tied.In China’s Wake reveals the surprising connections among these three phenomena. Nicholas Jepson shows how Chinese demand not only transformed commodity markets but also provided resource-rich states with the financial leeway to set their own policy agendas, insulated from the constraints and pressures of capital markets and multilateral creditors such as the International Monetary Fund. He combines analysis of China-led structural change with fine-grained detail on how the boom played out across fifteen different resource-rich countries. Jepson identifies five types of response to boom conditions among resource exporters, each one corresponding to a particular pattern of domestic social and political dynamics. Three of these represent fundamental breaks with dominant liberal orthodoxy—and would have been infeasible without spiraling Chinese demand. Jepson also examines the end of the boom and its consequences, as well as the possible implications of future China-driven upheavals. Combining a novel theoretical approach with detailed empirical analysis at national and global scales, In China’s Wake is an important contribution to global political economy and international development studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChinaxForeign economic relationszDeveloping countries. 0aDeveloping countriesxForeign economic relationszChina. 0aEconomic developmentzDeveloping countries. 0aNatural resourceszDeveloping countries. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / Economics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G